This paper is likely to belong to the Speech and Dialogue (cs.SD) sub-category as it focuses on improving the acoustic model topology for speech recognition. Additionally, it may also belong to the Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category as speech recognition is a subfield of natural language processing. The use of deep CNNs and optimization techniques also suggests that it could belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of ResNet-50, which is a popular architecture in computer vision, indicating that it could belong to the Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (cs.CV) sub-category. Finally, the use of scaled exponential linear units (SELU) suggests that it could belong to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category, which focuses on neural network architectures and optimization techniques.
